Figure 6 shows power-law frequency spectra, with break points (blue and red dots) that separate steepening power-laws representing the different stages of Alfvénic turbulent cascade. The break points move to lower frequencies with increasing helioradius. Thus, turbulence in fast solar wind streams and also in slower streams that are far from the plasma and current sheets are dominated by Alfvénic fluctuations (Bruno and Carbone 2005, 2013; Telloni et al. 2015). This helioradial evolution is evidence for an ongoing non-linear cascade with heating rates estimated to be in the range required to explain the in-situ heating of the solar wind (Vasquez et al. 2007). However, the overall way in which energy per unit mass (E\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
